data.text:
The Czechoslovak men's national ice hockey team is the national ice hockey team of Czechoslovakia. It is one of the most successful national ice hockey teams in the world and a member of the so-called "Big Six", the unofficial group of six of the strongest men's ice hockey nations, along with Canada, Finland, the Soviet Union, Sweden and the United States. It is controlled by the Czechoslovak Ice Hockey Association.

History[]

The successor to the Bohemian national ice hockey team, which was a European power prior to World War I, the Czechoslovak national team made its international debut at the 1920 Summer Olympics hockey tournament, staged in Antwerp, Belgium. A 1-0 victory over Sweden earned them the bronze medal. Following the country's success as the tournament, the ice hockey section of the ČSSH was spun off into the Československý svaz kanadského hokeje (ČSSKH; in English, Czechoslovak Union of Canadian Hockey).

The Czechoslovaks traveled to Sweden to play in the 1921 European Championship, the only European country to make the trip. The Swedes won by a score of 7-4. The Czechoslovak federation was short on money and a very mild winter in Prague had only allowed four days where the weather outside was suitable for skating. However, the national team players all wanted to travel to Sweden to defend their 1914 European title (won as Bohemia). They had also promised the Swedes that they would come and play following their win over them at the 1920 Olympic tournament. They reclaimed the mantle of European champions in 1922, exacting revenge on Sweden in the deciding game, 3–2. This was the first time Josef Maleček wore his country's colors internationally. The 18-year-old played sparingly at the tournament but he would soon blossom into a star and become the most decorated player in inter-war European hockey.

A dispute between the ČSSKH and the club AC Sparta Praha, which formed their own association, the Czechoslovak Association of Canadian Hockey (Československá asociace kanadského hokeje, ČSAKH) resulted in a weaker roster and a poor finish at the 1924 Winter Olympics, as the team finished fifth at the tournament.

The two rival federations settled their differences and re-unified prior to the 1925 European Championship, which was hosted at home ice in Štrbské Pleso and Starý Smokovec in the Tatra mountains. In a dominant performance, the national team won all three games while failing to concede a goal. They finishing in second place at the 1926 European Championship behind Switzerland, followed by two weak performances as they finished fifth a year later and seventh at the 1928 Winter Olympics. A 2-1 overtime victory over Poland secured another championship for Czechoslovakia at the 1929 European Championship.

The country's first artificial ice rink, the Zimní stadión Štvanice, opened in Prague in 1931. The facility played host to the 1933 World Ice Hockey Championships, where Czechoslovakia won the bronze medal (finishing behind the U.S. and Canada) and were proclaimed European champions. The sport exploded in popularity in the country after this event. The Zimní stadión later hosted the 1938 World Ice Hockey Championships, where the host country again claimed third place.

The national team returned to play in the 1947 World Championship and promptly established themselves as the best team in Europe, becoming the first team from the continent to win three World Championships (1947, 1949 and 1950). This marked the first "Golden Generation" (Czech: Zlatá generace, Slovak: Zlatá generácia) Czechoslovak ice hockey, led by Vladimír Zábrodský. They won the silver medals at the 1948 Winter Olympics, finishing behind the reigning champions Canada. In 1949 Czechoslovakia overcame tragedy to win their second world championship and ninth European Championship. In November 1948 six Czechoslovak players (Ladislav Troják, Karel Stibor, Zdeněk Jarkovský, Vilibald Šťovík, Miloslav Pokorný and defenseman Zdeněk Švarc) were lost when their plane went missing crossing the English Channel. Despite the key losses to their roster, they defeated the Sudbury Wolves, Canada's representative, three to two. It was only the third defeat for the Canadians at a World Championship. The Americans were able to top the Czechs in the final round, which earned them a bronze medal. However, the Czechoslovaks clinched the gold with a 3-0 win over the hosts Sweden on the last day of the tournament. At the 1950 London World Championship they defended their title for a third consecutive time. They won additional silver medals at the 1951 and 1953 World Championships, losing to Canada and Sweden, respectively) and secured the bronze medals at the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo.

After the arrival of the Soviet Union on the international hockey scene in the 1950s, the Czechoslovaks were remarkably consistent in international play, medaling numerous times at the World Championship and Olympic tournaments. They regularly fought Sweden and Canada for silver and bronze medals, and sometimes beat the Soviets. The 1970 World Championship in Montreal and Winnipeg was the first true best-on-best world championship in hockey history as it allowed any player to represent their team regardless of amateur or professional status. As a result, the Czechoslovak national team could call upon the services of Stan Mikita, star player of the Chicago Black Hawks of the National Hockey League (NHL), and was generally regarded as one of the best centre of the 1960s. With a new tournament format, Czechoslovakia defeated Sweden in the bronze medal game 3–2. However, they would not win the gold again until the 1973 World Championships in Stockholm, where they defeated the Soviet Union 3–2. Strong goaltending and defensive corps were key in the victory.Jiří Holeček won the tournament's best goaltender award.

The 1970s brought the second Golden Generation with players like Holeček, Vladimír Dzurilla, Oldřich Machač, František Pospíšil, Jiří Bubla, Milan Nový, Josef Augusta, Jiří Holík, Vladimír Martinec, Ivan Hlinka and Václav Nedomanský. At the 1976 Olympics, the main rivalry in the tournament was between the Soviet and Czechoslovak national teams. Despite suffering from influenza throughout the tournament, Czechoslovakia played against the Soviets in the deciding game. They were up 2–0 after the first period. In the second, the score was tied by Vladimir Shadrin and Vladimir Petrov. Eight minutes before the end of the game Eduard Novák scored the third goal for the Czechoslovak team, but a subsequent goal by Aleksandr Yakushev tied the game again. One minute later, at 56:01, Nedomanský scored the deciding goal, leading Czechoslovakia to victory 4–3 and securing their first ever Olympic gold medal. At the 1977 World Championship, they lost only one game and swept the tournament awards (Jiří Holeček - goaltender, František Pospíšil - defenseman, Vladimír Martinec - forward). They additionally reached the finals in 1974 and 1975, losing to the Soviet Union 1–3 and Canada 4–5 in overtime, respectively. The tournaments in 1970 and 1975 established that Czechoslovakia could compete with the Canadian NHL stars in the eyes of the Canadian public. Nedomanský became one of the first European players to make an impact in the National Hockey League (NHL), paving the way for future generations of players.

By the mid 1980s players such as the Šťastný brothers (Peter Márian and Anton) were NHL stars while Jiří Dudáček, Miroslav Fryčer, Dárius Rusnák, Peter Ihnačák and Petr Svoboda were playing major roles on NHL teams. At home, players like Vladimír Růžička and Michal Pivoňka were regular contributors to the national team and were NHL players during the second half of the decade. The 1980s brought tighter competition from the United States and Sweden, but Czechoslovakia managed to secure bronze medals in 1981 and 1989, a silver medal in 1982 and winning gold at home ice in 1985, defeating Canada 5–3 in the final. They also won a silver medal at the 1984 Winter Olympics in Sarajevo, falling to the Soviets in the decisive game.

Following a couple of dissapointing tournaments in the early 1990s, coaches Ivan Hlinka and Peter Šťastný first led the team to their crowning achievement, the gold medal at the 1998 Winter Olympics. Canada, the United States and Sweden were considered the favourites with rosters stocked with NHL stars and future Hall of Famers. However, Czechoslovakia's defensive neutral zone trap system and stellar goaltending by Hašek, who allowed just six goals in six games, led the team to the final, where they defeated the Soviet Union 1–0. From 1998 to 2001 the Czechoslovaks would dominate international hockey, three straight gold medals at the IIHF world championships from 1999 to 2001. In 1999 in Norway the Czechoslovaks defeated Finland 3–1. The following year they defeated the Soviet hosts 4–3. At the 2001 World Championship in Germany they were down 0–2 in the finals against the Finns, but two goals and an overtime goal from Martin Procházka meant the third consecutive gold medal for Czechoslovakia. The third Golden Generation brought players NHL stars or stellar contributors like goaltender Dominik Hašek, defencemen Petr Svoboda, Jirí Šlégr, Roman Hamrlík, Richard Šmehlík, Ľubomír Sekeráš, Róbert Švehla and Ľubomír Višňovský, forwards Jaromír Jágr, Robert Reichel, Petr Nedvěd, Peter Bondra, Martin Ručinský, Martin Straka, Robert Lang, Miroslav Šatan, Zdeno Cíger, Pavol Demitra, Žigmund Pálffy and Jozef Stümpel.

In the next three years, the team only medalled once, a bronze medal in 2004. The following year, the Czechoslovaks won gold at the 2005 world championship in Prague and Bratislava, thus breaking the "world championship home ice curse". At the 2006 Winter Olympics, the Czechoslovaks won a bronze medal, defeating the Soviet Union 3–0 in the bronze medal game. At the 2007 world championship, the Czechoslovaks earned silver, falling to Sweden in the final. In the next three years, the team failed to get a medal at the world championships or the Olympics. In 2012 they won a silver medal, followed by a surprising gold medal on home ice at the 2015 world championship. After 2015 the Czechoslovaks have not won medals from either Olympic or IIHF tournaments, making it their longest medal drought in history.
